And ye shall know the truth, and the truth shall make you free. — John 8:32  As peaceful, law-abiding Christians, we do not advocate violence or any illegal activity for the following reasons:  These means and methods are counterproductive in this spiritual battle we currently face. Of course, there is a time for self-defense and fixing our long-term problems, as the Bible explains, but we are to be smart in these perilous times.  Behold, I send you forth as sheep in the midst of wolves: be ye therefore wise as serpents, and harmless as doves. — Matthew 10:16  Our focus here is to reach as many people as possible with the truth in a peaceful, effective, and law-abiding manner.  One of our valued readers left a comment about our mission that we believe does well in describing who we are — and what our aims are as Christians:  “I have found in your writing something that is lacking in most other Christian Israel, Christian Identity, Revisionist History, and JQ websites: Pastoral sense.  It is far too easy to latch onto the intellectual thrill of uncovering the conspiracy, or to lapse into hatred of those who perpetrate it.  You keep the focus squarely on Jesus Christ.  I am not above a little humor at the expense of Christ’s haters, or a momentary flash of anger at their wickedness, but I try to put it all in context. When the Kingdom is restored, none of this will matter.  I appreciate you as a ‘worker who has no need to be ashamed, rightly dividing the word of truth.'”  Who runs this website? A small group of non-denominational Christians, located in various parts of the world, contribute to this website.  We have chosen to be anonymous for two reasons:  This is not about us. Many people in the alt media seek attention and internet fame, but our only goal is to help you find the truth, which ultimately leads to true Christianity. We value our privacy and yours. (The truth and those espousing it are the enemy to those who hate the truth.) Finally, my brethren, be strong in the Lord, and in the power of his might. Put on the whole armour of God, that ye may be able to stand against the wiles of the devil. For we wrestle not against flesh and blood, but against principalities, against powers, against the rulers of the darkness of this world, against spiritual wickedness in high places. Wherefore take unto you the whole armour of God, that ye may be able to withstand in the evil day, and having done all, to stand. Name: Reichsmark - Wikipedia
sub_title: The Reichsmark (German: [ˈʁaɪçsˌmaʁk] (listeni); sign: ℛ︁ℳ︁; abbreviation: RM) was the currency of Germany from 1924 until 20 June 1948 in Trizone, where it was replaced by the Deutsche Mark, and until 23 June 1948 in the Soviet occupation zone of Germany , where it was replaced by the East German mark. The Reichsmark was subdivided into 100 Reichspfennige (Rpf[1] or ℛ︁₰). The Mark is an ancient Germanic weight measure, traditionally a half pound, later used for several coins; Reich (empire in English) comes from the official name for the German state from 1871 to 1945, Deutsches Reich.

Name: American Nazi Demonstration at SF State (1975) - Bay Area Television Archive
sub_title: KRON-TV News footage from April 19th 1975 featuring brief scenes from an American Nazi Party demonstration in San Francisco on 19th Avenue at Holloway, by San Francisco State College. Also views of angry protests from the Progressive Labor Party. Neo Nazi leader Alan Vincent tries to shout over the heckling with a speech: "White men and women around the world are watching and hoping that white American will show the way!" Voice over is provided throughout by KRON reporter Jack Bates. Note that an Oscar nominated documentary film was made in 1975 called The California Reich, which looks at Neo-Nazi groups in California and features Alan Vincent. Opening graphic designed by Carrie Hawks.

Name: American Nazi Party Rally Outside City Hall (1966) - Bay Area Television Archive
sub_title: KPIX News footage from 1966 featuring scenes from an American Nazi Party rally in downtown San Francisco. At one point a woman protester who is struggling with a policeman grabs a reporter's microphone and screams that: "They killed 6 brothers and sisters! I was in Auschwitz! The Jewish bible says an eye for an eye ... They're murderers ... No, it's not right!" Ends with an interview with Frank Quinn, Director of the San Francisco Human Rights Commission, who expresses his "deep anger" towards the rally but also concedes the American Nazi Party's right to express their political philosophy in public. Includes views of the Swastika symbol flying outside of San Francisco's City Hall, whilst a recording of the Star Spangled Banner is played. Opening graphic designed by Carrie Hawks.

Name: The California Reich - Wikipedia
sub_title: The California Reich was a 1975 documentary film on a group of neo-Nazis in Los Angeles, San Francisco and Tracy, California, USA. They were members of the National Socialist White People's Party, another name for the American Nazi Party that was started by George Lincoln Rockwell. It was screened at the 1976 Cannes Film Festival, but wasn't entered into the main competition.[2] It was also nominated for the Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature.[3]

Name: George Rockwell on US Nazi Motorcycle Core in San Francisco (1966) - Bay Area Television Archive
sub_title: KPIX news footage from c1966 with reporter Rollin Post featuring a press conference by the American Nazi Party, which plans to set up the headquarters of its Motorcycle Core in San Francisco. Includes views of members posing in front of a Swastika flag and scenes of their founder George L. Rockwell (1918-1967) speaking. Rockwell predicts that their first unit will be operating out of San Francisco by the spring of 1967 and explains the purpose of the core is: "To do everything possible to protect white people at any time when the police department may be overwhelmed." He goes on to confirm they have had no formal contact with the Hells Angels Motorcycle Group as yet. California Neo-Nazi leader Alan Vincent can be seen sat immediately to the left of Rockwell at the press conference.

Name: An Unexpected Partnership in WW2: Nazi Germany and the Republic of China | War History Online
sub_title: A quick first glance at these photos would have most military history enthusiasts fooled. You would be forgiven to assume that these are German-trained Imperial Japanese Army (IJA) personnel. But that could not be further from the truth – they are in fact Nazi-trained Chinese soldiers of the National Revolutionary Army (NRA), destined to fight Japanese invaders. The Wehrmacht officer is Chiang Wei-Kuo, adopted son of Chinese Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek. Chiang Wei-Kuo commanded a German Panzer during Anschluss, earned a commission as a Wehrmacht lieutenant in anticipation of Fall Weiss, before being recalled back to China.

Name: Dostoevsky on the Jews | National Vanguard
sub_title: As much as his people loved him, Dostoevsky in turn loved them — and despised their enemies and exploiters. Foremost among the latter were the Jews of Russia. In Dostoevsky’s time there were some three million of them, some descended from the Khazars, an Asiatic tribe of southern Russia which had converted to Judaism a millennium earlier, and some who had flocked into Russia from the West during the Middle Ages, when they were forcibly expelled from every country in western and central Europe.

Name: Mass-Producing Traditional Small Cities: Gottfried Feder's Vision for a Greater Nazi Germany - Tilman A. Schenk, Ray Bromley, 2003
sub_title: Gottfried Feder (1883-1941) joined the newly founded Nazi movement in 1919 and became a leading writer and spokesman on economics, architecture, and urban development. He condemned usury, finance capital, large corporations, metropolitan growth, and modernist architecture, and he advocated family-owned businesses, state enterprises, small cities, and “traditional” styles. After Hitler came to power, Feder worked in government, but he was marginalized in 1934 and appointed professor of planning at the Berlin Institute of Technology. There, he wrote Die neue Stadt (The New City), a major book published in 1939 but largely ignored in Germany—in wartime because it criticized big business and afterward because Feder was a leading Nazi. The book blends fascist, modernist, antiurban, and geopolitical visions to propose the construction of many new traditional cities of twenty thousand in supposedly sparsely populated eastern lands. It shows how innocuous planning ideas may be appropriated for sinister purposes of conquest and social engineering.

Name: Gottfried Feder
sub_title: In February 1920, the German Workers's Party published its first programme which became known as the "Twenty-Five Points". In the programme the party refused to accept the terms of the Versailles Treaty and called for the reunification of all German people. To reinforce their ideas on nationalism, equal rights were only to be given to German citizens. "Foreigners" and "aliens" would be denied these rights. To appeal to the working class and socialists, the programme included several measures that would redistribute income and war profits, profit-sharing in large industries, nationalization of trusts, increases in old-age pensions and free education. Feder greatly influenced the anti-capitalist aspect of the Nazi programme and insisted on phrases such as the need to "break the interest slavery of international capitalism" and the claim that Germany had become the "slave of the international stock market".
